<dl id="n38146a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38146a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38146a"> 146(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> I luft my / sloper forward / to m<font color="green">[r]</font><sup>o</sup> Ally / on the hills <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n38146a"><li>FW 37.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n38146a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n38146a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n38146a">MS BL 47475-106</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:123 <a name="bd8y" href="../../ff/fdra/bda.htm#bd8y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/bd8.htm#n38146a">Draft: I.2&sect;1.8</a>+/2.8+/3.8+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Each word should, so far as possible, be gesturally appropriate to its meaning, since it then becomes more natural and more durable. Thus the pantomimic symbolism of tongue-gesture might be used in the invention of new words, so that, for example <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> E (as in men) would denote a mid or medium position, EI a rising, AI a steeper rise, IE a falling, IA a steeper fall, while &Auml; as in hat (written phonetically &AElig;) would represent a <mark>sloping forward</mark>. <small> Sir Richard Paget, <a name="RPBP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RPBP"><cite title="source">Babel, or The Past, Present and Future of Human Speech</cite></a> (1930) 84-5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: That is, I lift my hat in the air [German <i>Luft</i>] </mm> </dd></dl>
